Here are the essential basic commands to check your Azure connection and existing resources:

1. Check Azure Login Status
bash
# Check if you're logged in and see account info
az account show

# List all subscriptions available to your account
az account list
2. Check Existing Resources
bash
# List all resource groups
az group list

# List all virtual machines in your subscription
az vm list

# List VMs with more details (including power state)
az vm list -o table

# List all disks
az disk list
3. Check Specific VM Details
bash
# Get details about a specific VM
az vm show --name <vm-name> --resource-group <resource-group-name>

# Check VM power state
az vm get-instance-view --name <vm-name> --resource-group <resource-group-name> --query "instanceView.statuses[1]" -o table

# List IP addresses of a VM
az vm list-ip-addresses --name <vm-name>
4. Quick Status Commands
bash
# One-liner to check login and list VMs
az account show && az vm list -o table

# Check available VM sizes in a region
az vm list-sizes --location "West US" -o table

# Check available VM images
az vm image list --offer UbuntuServer --sku 22_04-lts --all -o table
5. Most Useful for This Lab
bash
# Check current login
az account show --query "user.name" -o tsv

# See ALL resources you have access to
az resource list -o table

# Just show me my VMs and their states quickly
az vm list --show-details --query "[].{Name:name, ResourceGroup:resourceGroup, Status:powerState}" -o table
Run az account show first - if it returns your user info, you're connected. If you get an error, you need to login with az login -u <username> -p <password>.